      <body>
         <entry xml:id="duqarnin-ys"
            type="mainEntry"
            xml:lang="en"
            prev="#"
            next="#"
            source="Yalkut Shimoni">
            <form type="lemma">
               <orth type="lemma" xml:lang="jpa" opt="false" select="true">דוקרנין</orth>
               <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb" opt="false">dwqrnyn</orth>
               <pron notation="rabbinic">duqarnin</pron>
               <gramGrp>
                  <gram type="pos">noun</gram>
                  <gram type="gen">m.</gram>
               </gramGrp>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="duqarnin-ys-1">
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>rod, stick</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="grc">
                  <quote>δοκάριον</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example" xml:lang="jpa">
                  <quote>אם יאמר לך אדם הדא כוכבתא דצפרא איילתא דשחרא הוא, שקרנא הוא, פעמים פוחתת פעמים מוספת, אלא כמין שני 
                     <app>
                        <lem>דוקרנין</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S V W">תרתין קרנין</rdg>
                     </app> סלקין מן מדינחא ומנהרין לעלמא</quote>
                  <bibl>
                     <ref type="witness">Yalq 84</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">I 389: 95</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>R. Yose b. Avin said: If a man tells you that the morning star is the morning dawn he is speaking falsely, for sometimes it is earlier and sometimes later; but a rod of light, as it were, issues from the east and lights up the world. (Cf. Freedman / Simon I 440)</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <note>= <bibl type="ancient">GenR 50,10 [II 527: 3]</bibl> (<term xml:lang="jpa">דקרנין</term>); <bibl type="ancient">SekhṬ 19,15 [36]</bibl> (<term xml:lang="jpa">דוקרנא</term>)</note>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <note>Löw (Krauss ad loc.), <bibl type="modern">Levy I 385b</bibl>, <bibl type="modern">Sokoloff, DJPA 135b</bibl> render here Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">δίκρανον</term> „pitchfork“ (see <term xml:lang="jpa">דקרן</term> for <bibl type="ancient">GenR</bibl>). <bibl type="modern">AC III 134b</bibl> suggests also Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">δι</term> + Hebr. <term xml:lang="jpa">קרן</term> <term xml:lang="fjb">qrn</term> (corresponding to <bibl type="ancient">Yalq</bibl> S V W). The origin Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">δίκρανον</term> explains well the word in <bibl type="ancient">tMen 3 [529: 36]</bibl>, <bibl type="ancient">tKel (NM) 3 [583: 3]</bibl>.</note>
            <ref type="bibliography">
               <bibl>
                  <title>Krauss, LW II</title>
                  <citedRange>193b-194a</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </ref>
         </entry>
